''Of'' should never follow ''off''. It is grammatically wrong.  People use ''off of'' as a [[preposition]].

When individuals use it, grammarians think of it as a gap in a person's understanding of English grammar, thoughtlessness in a fast conversation, or stubbornness in not wanting to relinquish an old habit.

;Example 1:  Chip off <s>of</s> the old block.
;Example 2:  This is off <s>of</s> the topic.
;Example 3:  Take your hat off <s>of</s> the table.

----
Sometimes ''off of'' should be replaced with ''on''.
;Incorrect example 1:  Based ''off of'' quantum mechanics, an electron is both a wave and a particle. 
;Correct example 2: Based ''on'' quantum mechanics, an electron is both a wave and a particle.